WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.360
Yeah. So how do we make decisions using MRD in the modern era of treating ALL? So, of course,

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:09.740
all of us would like to have therapies that we can give. We cure our patients. We pat ourselves

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:13.260
on the back, move on to the next patient. However, all too often, there's residual disease.

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:18.700
And MRD is not a binary status. It's a spectrum of disease burden that is either detectable or

00:00:18.700 --> 00:00:24.620
not detectable. And with increasing or improved technologies, we can reach deeper levels.

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:29.000
But at some point, you reach a threshold of detection. I won't go through all the data

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.300
supporting why you should use the highest sensitivity methodology for quantifying MRD

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:38.000
in ALL. But suffice it to say, you should use the highest sensitivity. But at some point,

00:00:38.040 --> 00:00:42.440
you reach that threshold of detection. And you're still trying to guess, is your patient on the

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:46.920
green trajectory, meaning they're cured? Or are they on the red trajectory, meaning that they're

00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:51.580
still going to relapse? So we have to take other factors into account when making this assessment.

00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:58.820
And really, it boils down to their genotype. Because MRD is contextual with their genotype,

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:05.780
we have to interpret both together. Because in ALL, there are genotypes where if you reach MRD

00:01:05.780 --> 00:01:11.180
less than 10 to the minus 4, as shown here, your risk of relapse is exceptionally low. But there

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:16.920
are other genotypes that if you reach that level of MRD, you still have 20% to 25% risk of relapse.

00:01:16.920 --> 00:01:21.760
So we need to think about this as we're interpreting modern data. And there was indeed

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:28.200
a new paradigm for treating ALL that was presented with the ECOG-1910 trial, where adult patients

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:28.920
between age 3 and 5 were treated with MRD less than 10 to the minus 4. And there was indeed a new paradigm

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:35.440
30 and 70 with pH-negative B-cell ALL were treated initially with a asparaginase-containing

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:41.540
ECOG-2993 backbone regimen for induction and intensification. And then if they were MRD

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:46.160
negative, they were randomized to receive four cycles of blenatumab with four cycles of chemo,

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:49.480
or just the four cycles of chemo, and then go on to maintenance therapy.

00:01:50.140 --> 00:01:54.340
And everyone is familiar with the Kaplan-Meier curves on the right side of the slide that show

00:01:54.340 --> 00:01:58.820
those patients who got blenatumab for MRD-negative disease did extremely well.

00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:04.400
And I think a lot of people didn't read between the lines and understand that this represents

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:10.180
less than half of the patients that accrued to the trial. So 40% of patients never made it to

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:16.800
the randomization. And as you can see here, only 46% of the patients who enrolled in the trial

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:22.540
achieved MRD-negativity, maintained MRD-negativity through the induction intensification and got

00:02:22.540 --> 00:02:28.680
randomized. So everyone else is not represented on these Kaplan-Meier curves at all. The intention to

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:34.480
study outcomes have never seen the light of day. So we have to make a lot of inferences

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:40.420
on the basis of these data. For a short period of time, MRD-positive patients were also randomized,

00:02:40.420 --> 00:02:45.240
and those patients who received blenatumab for MRD-positive disease did well. This was considered

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:51.180
to be confirmatory of the BLAST trial. And after blenatumab was approved for treating MRD-positive

00:02:51.180 --> 00:02:58.380
disease, they needed to stop accruing to this arm. So the ECOG-Akron group did present this post-hoc

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:03.300
multivariate analysis to try and address whether transplant was useful for any of the patients on

00:03:03.300 --> 00:03:07.500
the trials. Transplant was not a specified therapy. It was left to the investigators whether to use

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:12.740
transplant. And basically by random chance, 22 patients on both the blen arm and the non-blen arm

00:03:12.740 --> 00:03:17.900
underwent transplant. And in this multivariate analysis, the use of transplantation did not

00:03:17.900 --> 00:03:24.220
have a significant impact on survival. Only the receipt or not of blenatumab or performance status

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:28.760
or a risk category was associated with benefit.

00:03:28.760 --> 00:03:34.780
So they took a little deeper dive and they show us on the left side, for all of the patients that

00:03:34.780 --> 00:03:39.900
received blenatumab, there does not appear to be a benefit to receiving an allogeneic transplant.

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:45.280
And furthermore, on the right side, for the patients that had an unfavorable risk category,

00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:51.760
if they received blenatumab, based on the numbers at the bottom, does not appear to be a benefit to

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:57.540
transplant. So we learn a little bit more as more data are released from this study. And Shira

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:04.820
is going to show you a subset analysis at IHA last year, where they only looked at the patients up to

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:10.900
age 55. So the ones that theoretically would be most potentially eligible for transplant. You can

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:17.340
see here that at enrollment, 53% of the patients had high risk disease. 66 of these patients had

00:04:17.340 --> 00:04:22.560
pH-like disease. I'm going to come back to this number of 66. But we can see even in this younger

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:28.580
group, still 40% of the patients never made it to transplant and fewer than half made it to the

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:32.680
randomization and fewer than half were MRD negative and made it to the randomization.

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:37.340
And again, the dropout is because patients either didn't achieve or maintain remission for those two

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:42.020
cycles of chemotherapy, or they had excess toxicities. So for the patients that did make

00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:48.040
it, they did very well with blenatumab, but we can see based on who got treated, who dropped out,

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:55.240
it's the high risk patients. So we go from 53% high risk at screening to 30% high risk at

00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:58.640
treatment at randomization. So a lot of those patients, again, high

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:04.140
risk are not represented on these Kaplan-Meier curves anywhere. So chemo blend is not an answer

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:10.480
for everyone. They did do another sub-analysis looking at the B-cerebral-like or pH-like

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:14.660
patients. And they showed that for those patients who got randomized to blenatumab,

00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:21.620
they had excellent outcomes. But this is only 19 of the 66 pH-like patients who were

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:28.280
enrolled at screening. So 47 pH-like patients dropped out because they could not achieve and

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:33.760
gain an MRD-negative remission. So they're not represented anywhere here. And on this Kaplan-Meier

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:38.940
curve, more than a third of patients got transplanted. So given all these caveats,

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:46.520
why is this even more impossible to interpret? Well, B-cerebral-like or pH-like disease is an

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:51.200
aggregate of more than 12 different genotypes based on gene expression profiling that makes

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:56.780
them look like pH-positive disease. But not all pH-like disease is created equal. This very nice

00:05:56.780 --> 00:05:58.560
study from the MD Anderson group is a study that was done in the United States. And it was done

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:04.980
by a group where a third of their patients referred for pH-negative or for B-cell ALL have

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:10.960
pH-like disease. And we can see that amongst the pH-like disease, two-thirds have CRLF2 abnormalities

00:06:10.960 --> 00:06:16.120
and they carry the highest risk, as you can see over on the right, for the worst outcomes. Whereas

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:22.300
the non-CRLF2 abnormal pH-like patients don't carry as much risk. So simply saying that B-cerebral-like

00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:28.060
patients can do well with chemo and blenatumab doesn't really tell us how to make decisions in

00:06:28.060 --> 00:06:28.520
the current climate. So we're going to look at the B-cerebral-like patients. And we're going to

00:06:28.520 --> 00:06:32.340
go back to the clinical setting because we actually need to know, are they CRLF2-like or are they other

00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:36.960
types such as abloplast kinase domain mutations? And why is this important? It's important because

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:41.180
we need to make the decision about whether to transplant. And transplant is the great equalizer

00:06:41.180 --> 00:06:46.540
in B-cell ALL, even for some of these high-risk genotypes, including pH-like. You can see they do

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:52.240
just as well with transplant as the non-PH-like patients. And this is true for all of the subsets

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:58.020
of pH-like disease, including the CRLF2 abnormal patients. What other data do we have? We have a

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:04.220
study using blenatumab with a 10403 regimen in a very similar way. They have very short follow-up

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:10.120
of just over a year. And it looks fantastic. But look, they transplanted half of the patients. And

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:14.460
they didn't tell us how they applied transplant across different genotypes. So again, we're left

00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:19.520
making inferences. The MD Anderson approach with hypercevad blenatumab is shown here. And I won't

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:23.820
go through all the details, but it will make a few points. These Kaplan-Meier curves are

00:07:23.820 --> 00:07:28.440
intentioned to treat. So we know from the initiation of therapy all the way through what is the outcome

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:32.880
for these patients. And we can see on the right, those patients had one or more high-risk features,

00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:38.360
do have a decrement in their survival. And Anderson, even though my friend Elias Shabor would

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:43.200
say he doesn't like to transplant ALL, they still transplanted a third of the patients on this

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:49.700
study. And so how do I put all these data together, taking all the caveats and trying to remove my

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:58.400
biases for transplantation and trying to really scrutinize the data? So for a standard and

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:03.220
objective approach, I think we can continue with chemotherapy, no transplant. If they're MRD

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:07.380
positive after blenatumab, they're going to have a problem. They can either go to a CAR-T cell if

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:13.340
they're still CD19 expressors, or potentially go to allotransplantation directly. For the high-risk

00:08:13.340 --> 00:08:18.760
patients, we need to really scrutinize both their response to the chemo and the response to blen.

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:24.520
And that's a strict interpretation of ECOG 1910. Because remember, those Kaplan-Meier curves only

00:08:24.520 --> 00:08:28.360
include people who were MRD negative after chemo before they got blen. So we need to really scrutinize

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:34.300
the blen. The blen was an immunologic consolidation for MRD negativity. So for the patients that do

00:08:34.300 --> 00:08:39.100
well with chemo and maintain an MRD negative response, I think even if they're high-risk,

00:08:39.100 --> 00:08:44.700
we can consider not taking those patients to transplant. I still have biases, as does everyone

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:49.800
else. I'm probably still going to transplant the KMT2A rearranged, probably still going to

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:54.180
transplant the CRLF2 rearranged until we have more data. But I do think that this is reasonable.

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:58.320
For patients that are MRD positive after chemotherapy with a high-risk genotype,

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:03.520
even if they become MRD negative after blen, I would not trust that to be a long-term remission.

00:09:03.660 --> 00:09:07.840
I'm going to favor taking those patients to transplant. And for the patients that become

00:09:07.840 --> 00:09:12.220
MRD positive after blen, whether or not they went to the blen, MRD positive or negative,

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:16.600
that's a patient that really has a problem. And again, I would favor taking them to a CAR-T-cell,

00:09:16.720 --> 00:09:21.860
if at all possible, or directly to an allotransplant. So I'm two minutes over time. I do

00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:26.040
apologize. That was very hard to go through in seven minutes. And I won't read my conclusions

00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:27.980
because they're all encapsulated in the final figure.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:28.880
And thank you very much.
